# ğŸ”¥ Firewall Configuration & Network Traffic Control (Linux)

## ğŸ“Œ Project Overview
This project demonstrates the implementation of a **Linux-based firewall** using **iptables** to control inbound and outbound network traffic.  
The objective is to **restrict unauthorized access**, **reduce attack surface**, and **validate firewall effectiveness** using network scanning tools.

---

## ğŸ¯ Objectives
- Configure firewall rules to filter network traffic
- Block unnecessary and insecure protocols
- Allow only required services (e.g., SSH)
- Detect and prevent unauthorized access attempts
- Validate firewall behavior using network scanning

---

## ğŸ›  Tools & Technologies
- Linux (Ubuntu / Kali Linux)
- iptables (Linux firewall utility)
- Nmap (Network scanning tool)
- VirtualBox (Lab environment)

---

## ğŸ§ª Lab Environment
- **Firewall System:** Linux VM (Ubuntu / Kali)
- **Test System:** Attacker / Client Machine
- **Network Mode:** NAT / Host-Only Adapter

---

## ğŸ” Firewall Rules Implemented

| Rule Description | Command | Purpose |
|------------------|--------|---------|
| List existing rules | `iptables -L` | View current firewall rules |
| Block ICMP (Ping) | `iptables -A INPUT -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -j DROP` | Prevent host discovery |
| Allow SSH | `iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT` | Enable secure remote access |
| Block specific IP | `iptables -A INPUT -s 192.168.1.100 -j DROP` | Block malicious host |
| View rules (verbose) | `iptables -L -v` | Monitor packet activity |
| Flush rules | `iptables -F` | Reset firewall configuration |

---

## ğŸ§ª Testing & Validation
- **Ping Test:** Verified ICMP blocking
- **Port Scanning:** Used Nmap to identify open and filtered ports
- **Rule Monitoring:** Checked packet and byte counters using verbose mode

Example:
nmap <target-ip>
